<TITLE> Rivaldo may quit Greece over legal wrangling </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ATHENS, April 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - World Cup winner Rivaldo has said he will leave AEK Athens to finish his career in Brazil if a court ruling does not award the club the Greek Super League title this week. Olympiakos Piraeus finished two points ahead of AEK after Sunday's last round of matches but could lose the title if the Lausanne-based Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) rules against them. "If we (AEK) are not vindicated I will ask the club president (Demis Nikolaidis) to release me from my contract so that I can leave Greece," Rivaldo told Greek media after AEK's 2-0 win over Asteras Tripolis. "I will probably go back to Brazil to finish my career," added Rivaldo, who was part of Brazil's 2002 World Cup-winning team. CAS is due to rule on a match played between Olympiakos and Apollon Kalamaria on Feb 3, which Olympiakos lost 1-0. They were awarded three points by the Greek Football Federation (EPO) because Apollon's Roman Wallner, signed in January, had already played for the Scottish clubs Falkirk and Hamilton. The 36-year old Rivaldo, who won three titles with Olympiakos before joining AEK last summer, scored the first goal in Sunday's win and later took a swipe at his former club. "I enjoyed winning this league title more than any I have won in Greece," he said. "A team that was not good enough to win the title on the pitch does not deserve the trophy. Football is a beautiful sport and should be played on the pitch
